Why do you take it along a subsequence, instead of along the filter of positive epsilons? With `tendsto_integral_filter_of_dominated_convergence`, your proof should generalize right away.

Thank you, this is obviously an improvement.

I fixed this, but my proof of `continuous_levyProkhorov_to_probabilityMeasure` still goes via sequential continuity. But since that is only the proof, not the statement, maybe that is not too bad.

In principle there should be a proof with filters, which should in fact be cleaner than my sequence proof. But at least for me, adding the epsilon of room with `exists_seq_strictAnti_tendsto` was easier than cleanly combining the neighborhood filter `ùìù ŒΩ` in probability measures with an extra `ùìù[>] 0` filter in the reals... With sequences, I just took a sequence of probability measures and a sequence of positive epsilons tending to zero, and paired them up, because both were indexed by natural numbers. I'm sure there exists a clean and clever filter magic for the same, but perhaps the sequence proof is acceptable? (Again, here it is only the proof, not the statement, that is affected by my clumsiness.)
